Q3. How many alphabets need to be there in a language if one were to make 1 million distinct 3 digit initials using the alphabets of the language?


10

3000000

100

Correct answer

3

Solution

Hide

This n^3 different initials = 1 million.

i.e. n^3 = 10^6 (1 million =10^6)

n^3 = 10^2

n = 10^2

n = 100

Hence, the language needs to have a minimum of 100 alphabets

Question 15

You didn't Attempt

 Consider a disk having 20 platters with single surface recording, each surface has 100 tracks and each track has 300 sectors and the capacity of each sector is 512 Bytes. What is the capacity of one cylinder?

2000 KB

3000 KB

Correct answer

4000

5000

Solution

Hide

A disk consists of many concentric platters. Each platter may have data recording either on one side or two sides, called surfaces. The data recording is done on tracks in terms of sectors. And a cylinder consists of concentric tracks from different surfaces. And from each surface only 1 track is part of the given cylinder, from the same surface each track will be part of a different cylinder. That's why in calculating the no. of sectors within a given cylinder we take only one track per surface. From the center of the disk, all the track-0s from all the platters will form cylinder-0, all the track-1s will form cylinder-1 and so on.

 

So, the capacity of 1 cylinder = 20*300*512 Bytes = 3000 KB

Question 20

You didn't Attempt

 Given the maximum lifetime of a segment is 30 sec and link capacity is 500Mbps, find the no. of bits required to avoid wrap-around during this time?




10 bits

23 bits

30 bits


34 bits

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

Given time = 30 sec, Bandwidth B = 500 Mbps  

In 1 sec ------ 500 Mb  

Therefore, 30 sec ----- 30 * 500 * 106 = 15 * 109 bits

No. of bits required to avoid wrap around = ceil(log2 (15*109)) bits              

= ceil(33.804) bits = 34 bits

Question 49

You didn't Attempt

 Direct Memory Access (DMA) takes 20 cycles for the initialization and 3 cycles for the transfer of each block. An interrupt program takes 4 cycles for every instruction and executed for every byte transferred. The block size of the system is 4 bytes. The speed up of DMA over interrupt programs achieved when a program of 8 instructions executed for transfer of 40 bytes is ________.


22

24

25

25.6

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

using interrupt mode:

Number of cycles required when a program of 8 instructions (remember each instruction takes 4 cycle) executed for transferring 40 bytes

( 4 * 8 ) * 40 = 1280


using DMA mode:

Number of cycle required when a program uses DMA mode 

20 + 3 * (40/4)

50 


speed up of DMA mode over interrupt mode 

1280/50 = 25.6

Question 51

You didn't Attempt

Consider the hashing table with m slots and n keys. If the expected number of probes in unsuccessful search is 3. The expected number of probes in a successful search is _______ (Upto 2 decimal places).


-

Your answer

1.64

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

Expected number of probes in unsuccessful search = 1/(1-)

where = load factor = n/m

Now 

m/(m-n) = 3

2m = 3n

n/m = .(i)

Expected number of probes in successful search = (1/)log(1/(1-))

using (i) we have

(3/2)log(3)

1.647

Question 56

You didn't Attempt

What is the time complexity of the following code?

void Knowledge(n)

 {

int i, j, k, count = 0;

  for(i = n/4; i <= n; i++)

       for( j = 1; j <= n/2; j = j*2)

           for(k = 1; k*k <= n; k++)

                 count++;

 }


 O(n^2 logn)


O(n^(3/2) logn)


Correct answer

 O(n(log^2)n)


O(n^3)


Solution

Hide

 If you see outer loop it is running for O(n)

inner loop for j-> logn times

inner loop for k-> sqrt(n)

Total time complexity -> n * n1/2 * logn

Question 60

You didn't Attempt

A 64 KB cache has a 256-byte block size and is 8-way set-associative. What is the number of TAG bits assuming that the physical address is 48-bits?

33

20

30

35

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

Size of the cache: 64KB

Size of the block: 256 Byte = 2^8

8-way set associative 

Physical address: 48-bit

 

No. of blocks in the cache = 64KB/256 Bytes = 256 

 

No. of sets = 256/8 = 32 = 2^5

 

No. of tag bits = 48 - 5 - 8 = 35
